WEBVTT

00:00:00.031 --> 00:00:02.260
Titanic had enough lifeboats to satisfy

00:00:02.260 --> 00:00:04.714
the law. That sentence sounds safe.

00:00:05.575 --> 00:00:08.337
In 1912, it was the problem.

00:00:09.619 --> 00:00:11.563
British rules measured lifeboats by

00:00:11.563 --> 00:00:14.987
tonnage. Above 10,000 tons, the top

00:00:14.987 --> 00:00:18.355
bracket required sixteen lifeboats for 990

00:00:18.355 --> 00:00:22.317
people. Titanic carried sixteen lifeboats

00:00:22.317 --> 00:00:25.523
and four collapsibles, enough for about

00:00:25.523 --> 00:00:30.038
1,176 people. More than 2,200 were aboard.

00:00:30.038 --> 00:00:31.580
The paperwork said compliant.

00:00:32.262 --> 00:00:33.363
The ship said otherwise.

00:00:34.164 --> 00:00:35.527
Some boats left underfilled.

00:00:36.189 --> 00:00:37.231
The law failed one way;

00:00:37.832 --> 00:00:40.795
evacuation failed another. Afterward,

00:00:40.795 --> 00:00:43.544
investigators pushed the correction: count

00:00:43.544 --> 00:00:45.304
people carried, not tonnage.

00:00:46.347 --> 00:00:48.670
Two years later, SOLAS turned that lesson

00:00:48.670 --> 00:00:51.711
into international rulemaking. The old

00:00:51.711 --> 00:00:53.670
category kept measuring yesterday's ship

00:00:53.670 --> 00:00:55.182
while approving tomorrow's risk.

00:00:55.984 --> 00:00:59.350
Small causes, massive consequences.
